li.p:
Because we are using m as a variable, we should not use that as our slope parameter. Instead, we'll just use the rise over run representation. The data support the hypothesis of a linear function if the slope is the same for any two points. We verify this directly. 
                         \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta m} &= \frac{h_2-h_1}{m_2-m_1} = \frac{70-82}{50-20} 
                         &= \frac{-12}{30} = -\frac{2}{5} 
                         \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta m} &= \frac{h_3-h_1}{m_3-m_1} = \frac{50-82}{100-20} 
                         &= \frac{-32}{80} = -\frac{2}{5} 
                         \frac{\Delta h}{\Delta m} &= \frac{h_3-h_2}{m_3-m_2} = \frac{50-70}{100-50} 
                         &= \frac{-20}{50} = -\frac{2}{5} 
                     Once we have the slope, we could use any single data point to find the equation. If we use (m,h) = (20,82), we have the pointslope form  f(m) = h = -\frac{2}{5}(m-20)+82.  It is not necessary to rewrite the equation in slopeintercept form.

image.latex-image-code:

\tikzset{%
}
\begin{tikzpicture}
    \begin{axis}[
        width=2.5in, height=2.5in,
        xmin=0,xmax=120,
        ymin=0,ymax=100,
        xlabel={$m$}, ylabel={$h$},
        grid=both,
        minor x tick num={4},
        minor y tick num={1},
        legend style={at={(0,0)}, anchor=south west},
        every axis legend/.append style={nodes={right}}
    ]

    \addplot[blue, thick, samples=30, domain=0:120]
        ({x}, {-2*x/5+90});
    \addplot[
        only marks,
        color=blue
    ] table {
        20 82
        50 70
        100 50
    };
    \legend {$h=-\frac{2}{5}(m-20)+82$}
    \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}


\tikzset{%
}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
    width=2.5in,
    height=2.5in,
    xmin=-5,xmax=5,
    ymin=-10,ymax=20,
    xlabel={$x$},
    ylabel={$y$},
    legend style={at={(0,0)}, anchor=south west},
    every axis legend/.append style={nodes={right}}
]

\addplot[blue, thick, samples=30, domain=-5:5]
    ({x}, {x^2});
\addplot[red, thick, samples=30, domain=0:5]
    ({x}, {6*(x-3)+9});
\addplot[
    only marks,
    color=blue
] table {
    3 9
};
\legend {$y=x^2$,$y=6(x-3)+9$}
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}


\tikzset{%
}
\begin{tikzpicture}[x=0.5cm,y=2cm]
\draw[<->] (-4.5,0) -- (12.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
\foreach \x in {-4, -3, ..., 12}
    \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node[below] {\x};
\draw[<->] (-4.5,-1) -- (12.5,-1) node[right] {$y$};
\foreach \x in {-4, -3, ..., 12}
    \draw (\x,-0.9) -- (\x,-1.1) node[below] {\x};
\draw [very thick, black, ->] (1,0) -- (3,-1);
\draw [very thick, black, ->] (2,0) -- (1,-1);
\draw [thick, dashed, black, ->] (3,0) -- (-1,-1);

\draw [very thick, red, ->] (1,0.1) -- (2,0.1) node[pos=0.5, above] {$\Delta x$};
\draw [very thick, blue, ->] (3,-0.9) -- (1,-0.9) node[pos=0.5, above] {$\Delta y$};
\end{tikzpicture}
